BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:arts-council-wales-festivals-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260729
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260730
SUMMARY:Deadline: Arts Council of Wales: Festivals (2026 rounds)
DESCRIPTION:Festivals is one of the new National Lottery programmes Arts Co
 uncil of Wales launched on 13 April 2026\, and it is the clearest organisa
 tion-facing route for funding a public festival in Wales. It supports focu
 sed\, time-limited festivals delivering high-quality arts programmes to br
 oad audiences\, in a single artform or mixed artforms\, with preference gi
 ven to festivals that commission\, create and present new artistic work. G
 rants run GBP 500 to 100\,000 across four tiers\, with the tier ceiling ti
 ed to how long the festival has been established. Match funding is mandato
 ry: the Council covers at most 75 percent of eligible costs and in-kind su
 pport is capped at 10 percent. There are two deadlines in 2026\, both at 1
 pm: Wednesday 29 July 2026 and Wednesday 16 December 2026. TIMING RULE: a 
 minimum of twelve working weeks must fall between the deadline and the pro
 ject start date\, so activity applied for in the July round cannot begin b
 efore roughly late October 2026. Retrospective costs are ineligible. Indiv
 idual artists cannot apply.\n\nOrganisation: Arts Council of Wales\nLocati
 on: Festival must take place in Wales and demonstrate cultural value to th
 e local community. Welsh language integration expected.\nAward: GBP 500 to
  100\,000 across four tiers: Small up to GBP 10\,000\; Large up to GBP 35\
 ,000 (1+ year track record)\; Large up to GBP 60\,000 (3+ years\, regional
  significance\, 2+ day programme)\; Large up to GBP 100\,000 (5+ years\, n
 ational significance). Co-financing mandatory: the Council funds a maximum
  of 75 percent of eligible costs\, so at least 25 percent of project incom
 e must come from non-Arts Council and non-Lottery sources\, of which no mo
 re than 10 percent may be in-kind. No application fee.\nDuration: One or t
 wo years of festival activity\; two-year applications require a track reco
 rd and development plan.\n\nMore: https://arts.wales/festivals-0?utm_sourc
 e=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://arts.wales/festivals-0?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&ut
 m_medium=referral
LOCATION:Festival must take place in Wales and demonstrate cultural value t
 o the local community. Welsh language integration expected.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:arts-council-wales-create-and-engage-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260729
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260730
SUMMARY:Deadline: Arts Council of Wales: Create and Engage (2026 rounds)
DESCRIPTION:Create and Engage is Arts Council of Wales's general-purpose Na
 tional Lottery programme for making and presenting arts work\, launched al
 ongside Festivals in April 2026\, and is the natural fit for exhibitions\,
  public programmes\, touring and participatory events that are not structu
 red as a festival. It funds creation\, presentation\, programming\, tourin
 g\, community participation and\, for organisations only\, professional de
 velopment. Small awards go up to GBP 10\,000 and large awards run GBP 10\,
 001 to 60\,000\, with up to GBP 100\,000 possible in exceptional cases wit
 h advance manager approval. At least 10 percent of project costs must come
  from non-Council\, non-Lottery sources\, a notably lighter co-financing b
 urden than the Festivals fund's 25 percent. TIMING RULES: Small Create and
  Engage is rolling with no set deadlines but requires a minimum of 10 work
 ing weeks between submission and project start\; Large Create and Engage h
 as fixed 1pm deadlines on 29 July 2026\, 30 September 2026 and 16 December
  2026\, with a minimum of 12 working weeks between deadline and project st
 art. Non-UK organisations can participate as partners but cannot lead. App
 licants cannot have an application in to more than one Arts Council fund a
 t the same time.\n\nOrganisation: Arts Council of Wales\nLocation: Project
 s must take place mainly in Wales. Individual applicants must be Wales-bas
 ed\; organisations outside the UK may take part as partners provided a UK-
 based eligible organisation leads.\nAward: Small awards up to GBP 10\,000\
 ; Large awards GBP 10\,001 to 60\,000\; exceptionally up to GBP 100\,000 w
 ith prior approval from an Arts Council manager. At least 10 percent of pr
 oject costs must come from non-Arts Council and non-Lottery sources. No ap
 plication fee.\nDuration: Project-length\; activity must not already be un
 derway at the point of application.\n\nMore: https://arts.wales/funding/in
 dividuals/create-and-engage?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
URL:https://arts.wales/funding/individuals/create-and-engage?utm_source=art
 ificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Projects must take place mainly in Wales. Individual applicants mu
 st be Wales-based\; organisations outside the UK may take part as partners
  provided a UK-based eligible organisation leads.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:acni-aidf-organisations-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260730
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260731
SUMMARY:Deadline: Arts Council of Northern Ireland: Artists' International 
 Development Fund for Organisations (2026)
DESCRIPTION:The Artists' International Development Fund (Organisations) is 
 Arts Council of Northern Ireland's route for NI-based arts organisations t
 o take a first substantive step into international working. It is the orga
 nisations counterpart to the individual-artist AIDF under the Support for 
 the Individual Artist Programme\, which is a separate scheme with its own 
 amount band. Grants run GBP 1\,000 to 7\,000 and cover art materials\, res
 idency costs\, travel including airfare and mileage\, artistic and technic
 al fees for production or post-production\, venue hire\, and equipment cap
 ped at 50 percent of the request value. The deadline is Thursday 30 July 2
 026 at 12:00 noon\, and the online system closes precisely at noon. Applic
 ants must be NI-based\, must have received recognition for their work ther
 e\, and must not already have extensive international experience. The appl
 ication must evidence genuine interest from an overseas partner or host\, 
 so a confirmed international invitation\, residency offer or presentation 
 opportunity is effectively a precondition.\n\nOrganisation: Arts Council o
 f Northern Ireland\nLocation: Applicant organisations must be based in Nor
 thern Ireland\; the funded activity takes place internationally\, with an 
 overseas partner or host.\nAward: GBP 1\,000 to 7\,000. Covers art materia
 ls\, residency costs\, travel (mileage at 25.7p per mile plus airfare)\, a
 rtistic and technical fees for production or post-production\, venue hire\
 , project equipment capped at 50 percent of the request value\, and IT equ
 ipment up to GBP 1\,200 for laptops or GBP 500 for tablets. No application
  fee.\nDuration: Short\, early-stage international development activity.\n
 \nMore: https://artscouncil-ni.org/funding-for-organisations/artists-inter
 national-development-fund-organisations?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantd
 esk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://artscouncil-ni.org/funding-for-organisations/artists-internatio
 nal-development-fund-organisations?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&u
 tm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Applicant organisations must be based in Northern Ireland\; the fu
 nded activity takes place internationally\, with an overseas partner or ho
 st.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:innovate-uk-next-wave-createch-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260811
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260812
SUMMARY:Deadline: Innovate UK: Next Wave Breakthrough Wave 1\, Createch (20
 26)
DESCRIPTION:Next Wave Breakthrough Wave 1 is Innovate UK's current open Cre
 atech competition\, investing up to GBP 10 million in early-stage innovati
 on at the intersection of creative technology and the frontier industries 
 named in the Industrial Strategy: video games\, advertising and marketing\
 , film and television\, and music and the performing and visual arts. It f
 unds industrial research to take innovations beyond proof of concept and d
 e-risk future investment\, with individual projects between GBP 100\,000 a
 nd 500\,000 in total costs. Grant rates depend on organisation size\, from
  70 percent for micro and small enterprises down to 50 percent for large o
 rganisations\, so applicants must supply match funding for the remainder. 
 The lead must be a UK-registered SME\; non-profits and CICs are barred fro
 m leading\, though they can participate as collaborators alongside a comme
 rcial lead. Non-funded partners may be based internationally. The competit
 ion opened 23 June 2026 and closes 11 August 2026 at 11:00am UK time. NOTE
  ON FIT: this is an R&D competition for creative-technology product develo
 pment\, not a fund for delivering festivals or exhibitions\, so it suits a
 n organisation whose work can be framed as industrial research with a comm
 ercial SME lead.\n\nOrganisation: Innovate UK\, UK Research and Innovation
 \nLocation: United Kingdom. Project work must be carried out in the UK\, r
 esults exploited in the UK\, and most funding spent in the UK.\nAward: GBP
  100\,000 to 500\,000 total project costs from a GBP 10 million fund\; no 
 organisation may receive more than GBP 3 million across the programme. Gra
 nt intervention rates for industrial research: up to 70 percent for micro 
 and small enterprises\, 60 percent for medium\, 50 percent for large. Rese
 arch organisations doing non-economic work can claim up to 100 percent\, o
 r 80 percent of full economic cost for academic institutions. The balance 
 is match funding. No application fee.\nDuration: 9 to 12 months\; projects
  must start by 1 January 2027 and end by 31 December 2027.\n\nMore: https:
 //apply-for-innovation-funding.service.gov.uk/competition/2517/overview/6f
 f2066d-4639-44e6-bb4f-ce7099222739?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&u
 tm_medium=referral
URL:https://apply-for-innovation-funding.service.gov.uk/competition/2517/ov
 erview/6ff2066d-4639-44e6-bb4f-ce7099222739?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United Kingdom. Project work must be carried out in the UK\, resul
 ts exploited in the UK\, and most funding spent in the UK.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:henry-moore-grants-autumn-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Henry Moore Foundation: Henry Moore Grants (Autumn 2026 r
 ound)
DESCRIPTION:Henry Moore Grants fund exhibitions\, exhibition catalogues\, s
 culpture commissions\, conferences\, non-commercial publications\, researc
 h\, and the development of collections through acquisition\, conservation\
 , cataloguing and display. The programme distributes roughly GBP 750\,000 
 a year across four assessment rounds\, each with a one-month application w
 indow. Maximum awards are GBP 20\,000 for New Projects and Commissions\, G
 BP 5\,000 for Conferences\, Lectures and Publications\, and GBP 2\,500 for
  individual Research and Travel. Applicants must be non-profit organisatio
 ns operating for at least 12 months\, and both UK and international bodies
  may apply\, which makes this unusually open among UK trusts. TIMING RULE:
  decisions arrive approximately six to eight weeks after each closing date
 \, and projects funded in a given round cannot begin before a fixed date r
 oughly four months after the deadline. Remaining 2026 windows are 1 August
  to 1 September 2026 (projects starting 1 January 2027 or later) and 1 Nov
 ember to 1 December 2026 (projects starting 1 April 2027 or later). The sc
 ulpture focus is a hard constraint\, so media-arts or digital-culture proj
 ects qualify only where sculpture or expanded three-dimensional practice i
 s genuinely central. Residencies and individual artists developing their o
 wn practice are excluded.\n\nOrganisation: Henry Moore Foundation\nLocatio
 n: Anywhere. The Foundation welcomes applications from UK and internationa
 l non-profit organisations.\nAward: Up to GBP 20\,000 for New Projects and
  Commissions\, Acquisitions and Collections\, and Long-Term Research. Conf
 erences\, Lectures and Publications up to GBP 5\,000. Research and Travel 
 (individuals) up to GBP 2\,500. Roughly GBP 750\,000 distributed a year. T
 he Foundation does not normally fund whole project costs and expects other
  funding to have been applied for. No application fee.\nDuration: Project-
 length\; grant payments must be claimed within 3 years of the offer date.\
 n\nMore: https://henry-moore.org/what-we-do/grants-fellowships/?utm_source
 =artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://henry-moore.org/what-we-do/grants-fellowships/?utm_source=artif
 icialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Anywhere. The Foundation welcomes applications from UK and interna
 tional non-profit organisations.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:acni-rural-engagement-arts-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260924
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260925
SUMMARY:Deadline: Arts Council of Northern Ireland: National Lottery Rural 
 Engagement Arts Programme (2026)
DESCRIPTION:The National Lottery Rural Engagement Arts Programme funds orga
 nisations to deliver arts activity in rural Northern Ireland\, addressing 
 isolation and social inclusion. It supports either a single one-off projec
 t or a multi-event public programme\, making it usable for exhibitions\, w
 orkshops\, touring events and community-facing digital or media arts work.
  Grants range from GBP 500 to 10\,000\, covering artist fees\, transport\,
  materials\, venue hire\, accessibility support\, volunteer expenses\, eva
 luation\, and equipment up to 50 percent of the request value. The deadlin
 e is Thursday 24 September 2026 at 12:00 noon\, and the online system clos
 es precisely at noon with no late or incomplete submissions accepted. TIMI
 NG RULE: funded activity must fall between 1 December 2026 and 30 November
  2027\, setting an effective earliest start date of roughly ten weeks afte
 r the deadline. Registered charities\, formally constituted non-profit gro
 ups\, local authorities and arts organisations are eligible\, including bo
 dies based outside Northern Ireland where the benefit accrues to rural NI 
 residents. Consortium applications demonstrating partnership working are e
 xplicitly prioritised. The rural and community framing means creative-tech
 nology work qualifies only where framed for that audience.\n\nOrganisation
 : Arts Council of Northern Ireland\nLocation: Activity must target rural c
 ommunities in Northern Ireland per the NISRA 2015 settlement classificatio
 n. Organisations based outside Northern Ireland may apply if the project b
 enefits rural NI residents.\nAward: GBP 500 to 10\,000 per project. Eligib
 le costs include artist fees\, transport\, materials\, venue hire\, access
 ibility support\, equipment (capped at 50 percent of the request value)\, 
 volunteer expenses and evaluation. No application fee.\nDuration: Maximum 
 12 months\; activity must take place between 1 December 2026 and 30 Novemb
 er 2027.\n\nMore: https://artscouncil-ni.org/funding-for-organisations/rur
 al-engagement-arts-programme?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_med
 ium=referral
URL:https://artscouncil-ni.org/funding-for-organisations/rural-engagement-a
 rts-programme?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Activity must target rural communities in Northern Ireland per the
  NISRA 2015 settlement classification. Organisations based outside Norther
 n Ireland may apply if the project benefits rural NI residents.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ahrc-design-generators-round-two-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260929
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260930
SUMMARY:Deadline: AHRC: Design Generators Round Two (2026)
DESCRIPTION:Design Generators round two funds design-led research projects 
 combining design interventions with arts and humanities methodologies to c
 ontribute to the green transition. Eligible activity includes design resea
 rch prototyping\, circular business model exploration\, strengthening thir
 d-sector resilience\, skills development\, policy and strategy work\, and 
 public engagement programmes\, so exhibition-style and public-facing outpu
 ts are in scope where they sit inside a research project. Awards are GBP 1
 50\,000 to 200\,000 at 100 percent full economic cost with AHRC paying 80 
 percent\, meaning the host organisation carries a 20 percent institutional
  contribution. The lead must be a postdoctoral-standing researcher at an A
 HRC-eligible UK research organisation\, and every project must pair that l
 ead with at least one non-academic co-lead from business\, the public sect
 or\, the third sector or a community organisation\, which is the practical
  entry point for an arts organisation. Freelancers and independent consult
 ants cannot lead. The opportunity opened 21 July 2026 and closes 29 Septem
 ber 2026 at 4:00pm UK time. Decision lag is roughly three months from the 
 deadline. IMPORTANT: this round explicitly excludes international stakehol
 ders and international activity\, so non-UK partners cannot be involved.\n
 \nOrganisation: Arts and Humanities Research Council (AHRC)\, UK Research 
 and Innovation\nLocation: United Kingdom. Lead applicant must be employed 
 by\, or hold a formal written arrangement with\, a UK research organisatio
 n eligible for AHRC funding. Project activities must take place in the UK.
 \nAward: GBP 150\,000 to 200\,000 per project at 100 percent full economic
  cost\; AHRC funds 80 percent and the host research organisation must cove
 r the remaining 20 percent. Total fund GBP 1\,000\,000\, approximately 5 a
 wards. Covers research staff time\, design prototyping\, partner costs and
  public engagement activity. Subcontractors and PhD studentships are not f
 undable. No application fee.\nDuration: 9 to 12 months\, with projects req
 uired to start by 1 February 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.ukri.org/opportuni
 ty/design-generators-round-two/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_
 medium=referral
URL:https://www.ukri.org/opportunity/design-generators-round-two/?utm_sourc
 e=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United Kingdom. Lead applicant must be employed by\, or hold a for
 mal written arrangement with\, a UK research organisation eligible for AHR
 C funding. Project activities must take place in the UK.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:jerwood-art-fund-commissions-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261002
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261003
SUMMARY:Deadline: Art Fund and Jerwood Foundation: Jerwood Art Fund Commiss
 ions (2026 round)
DESCRIPTION:Jerwood Art Fund Commissions is a partnership between Art Fund 
 and the Jerwood Foundation supporting museums and galleries to commission 
 early to mid-career artists to make work of exceptional innovation and qua
 lity. Two commissions of GBP 70\,000 to 100\,000 are awarded each year for
  three years\, covering the full cost of delivering and presenting the wor
 k\, which makes this one of the largest single commission awards available
  to UK public collections. All media are in scope\, including textiles\, s
 culpture\, ceramics\, film and photography. The resulting work is expected
  to enter a permanent public collection or be installed in the public real
 m. Applicants must be Accredited or provisionally Accredited public collec
 tions open at least half the week for six months of the year\, and partner
 ships between institutions are welcomed. Applications for the 2026 round o
 pened on 18 May 2026 and close on 2 October 2026\, submitted as a complete
 d Word form emailed to programmes@artfund.org. IMPORTANT: artists cannot a
 pply directly and must be put forward by an eligible host institution. Uns
 uccessful applicants cannot reapply with the same project. The permanent-c
 ollection outcome requirement means this suits commissioned artworks rathe
 r than time-limited festivals.\n\nOrganisation: Art Fund (in partnership w
 ith Jerwood Foundation)\nLocation: United Kingdom and the Channel Islands.
 \nAward: GBP 70\,000 to 100\,000 per commission\, two commissions awarded 
 per year for three years. Intended to cover all delivery and presentation 
 costs\, so no co-financing requirement is stated. No application fee.\nDur
 ation: Commission-length\; the programme runs as an annual award over thre
 e years.\n\nMore: https://www.artfund.org/professional/get-funding/program
 mes/jerwood-art-fund-commissions?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm
 _medium=referral
URL:https://www.artfund.org/professional/get-funding/programmes/jerwood-art
 -fund-commissions?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referra
 l
LOCATION:United Kingdom and the Channel Islands.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:jerwood-foundation-arts-grants-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270317
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270318
SUMMARY:Deadline: Jerwood Foundation: Arts Grants (2027 round)
DESCRIPTION:The Jerwood Foundation makes grants to UK organisations for pub
 lic-facing arts activity across theatre\, music\, dance\, visual arts and 
 literature\, including artist development programmes\, commissions\, resid
 encies and projects involving the Jerwood Collection. Awards have historic
 ally gone as high as GBP 200\,000\, though the Foundation states most gran
 ts are much smaller. Applications are single-stage: a written proposal of 
 no more than 10 sides of A4 excluding financial statements\, sent by email
  to info@jerwood.org or by post\, and it must include a summary sheet givi
 ng location\, amount requested\, timeline and audience figures. Applicatio
 ns missing that summary sheet are rejected automatically. The March 2026 d
 eadline has passed\; the next round opens 3 February 2027 at 9am and close
 s 17 March 2027 at 2pm\, with decisions on 28 April 2027 and all applicant
 s notified by 11 May 2027. TIMING RULE: activity funded in that round must
  start or open to the public between 1 July 2027 and 30 June 2028\, so the
 re is a long lead time and retrospective funding is impossible. Grants to 
 individuals are not made\, so artists must be supported through a host org
 anisation. Core costs and capital work are explicitly out of scope\, which
  makes this a good fit for discrete festivals\, exhibitions and public pro
 grammes.\n\nOrganisation: Jerwood Foundation\nLocation: United Kingdom. Ap
 plicants must be UK registered charities or UK limited companies.\nAward: 
 No published minimum or maximum. Previous awards have reached up to GBP 20
 0\,000\, but most grants are considerably smaller. Funds project and activ
 ity costs. No formal match-funding requirement\, but a fundraising strateg
 y must be submitted. No application fee.\nDuration: Activity for this roun
 d must start or open to the public between 1 July 2027 and 30 June 2028.\n
 \nMore: https://jerwood.org/funding/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk
 &utm_medium=referral
URL:https://jerwood.org/funding/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_
 medium=referral
LOCATION:United Kingdom. Applicants must be UK registered charities or UK l
 imited companies.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:bfi-national-lottery-discovery-feature-funding-2026@artificialnouveau.g
 ithub.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260813
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260814
SUMMARY:Deadline: BFI National Lottery Discovery Feature Funding (Debut Fic
 tion Features)
DESCRIPTION:Discovery is the debut-director production strand of the BFI Fi
 lmmaking Fund\, awarding up to GBP 1 million towards fiction features budg
 eted between GBP 1 million and GBP 3.5 million. It backs first-time featur
 e directors working alongside experienced producers\, and is structured so
  creative risk sits with a team rather than a lone filmmaker. ELIGIBILITY:
  applications must be made through a limited company registered and centra
 lly managed in the UK\, so unincorporated individuals cannot apply. A dedi
 cated lead producer with an established track record must submit\, and tha
 t producer must be someone other than the writer or director. The director
  must be making their first fiction feature\, meaning no prior feature at 
 or above a GBP 1 million budget and no prior commercial UK or Ireland thea
 trical distribution of a fiction feature. At least two people must be cred
 ited across the writer\, producer and director roles\, all aged 18 or over
  and not in full-time education. Projects need a fully developed script an
 d a runtime of at least 70 minutes. LIMITS: one application per production
  company\, producer and director per round\, and applications must arrive 
 at least 20 weeks before the proposed first day of principal photography. 
 ROUNDS: Round 2 closes at 5pm on Thursday 13 August 2026. Round 3 opens Th
 ursday 12 November 2026 and closes Wednesday 16 December 2026. Successful 
 applicants must publicly credit BFI National Lottery support.\n\nOrganisat
 ion: British Film Institute (BFI Filmmaking Fund\, National Lottery)\nLoca
 tion: United Kingdom (applications must come from a limited company regist
 ered and centrally managed in the UK)\nAward: Up to GBP 1\,000\,000 of Nat
 ional Lottery funding towards a fiction feature with a production budget b
 etween GBP 1\,000\,000 and GBP 3\,500\,000. No application fee.\nDuration:
  Single production award\; apply at least 20 weeks before the first day of
  principal photography. Decisions in principle within roughly 12 weeks of 
 the round closing.\n\nMore: https://www.bfi.org.uk/get-funding-support/cre
 ate-films-tv-or-new-formats-storytelling/bfi-filmmaking-fund-discovery-imp
 act-feature-funding?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
URL:https://www.bfi.org.uk/get-funding-support/create-films-tv-or-new-forma
 ts-storytelling/bfi-filmmaking-fund-discovery-impact-feature-funding?utm_s
 ource=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United Kingdom (applications must come from a limited company regi
 stered and centrally managed in the UK)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:uk-global-screen-fund-video-game-release-2026@artificialnouveau.github.
 io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260814
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260815
SUMMARY:Deadline: UK Global Screen Fund: International Distribution\, Video
  Game Release Funding
DESCRIPTION:The newest strand of the UK Global Screen Fund extends the fund
 's international-distribution logic from film into UK independent narrativ
 e video games. It supports marketing and release activity for games with d
 emonstrable international appeal and sales potential\, awarding non-recoup
 able grants to help UK studios reach overseas players. ELIGIBILITY: applic
 ations must be made by the UK-based development studio deemed the lead dev
 eloper for the game\, and only narrative video games qualify. One applicat
 ion per game. The wider UKGSF requirement that applicants be independent s
 creen-sector companies registered and centrally managed in the UK applies.
  TIMING: the round opened 14 May 2026 and closes at 12pm on Friday 14 Augu
 st 2026\, making it one of the few hard-deadline BFI opportunities current
 ly live. Separately\, applications must be filed at least eight weeks befo
 re the funded activity starts\, so a game releasing in early autumn may fa
 ll outside the window even if the application lands before 14 August. NOTE
 : award amounts are not published on the fund page\, so treat the range as
  unknown rather than estimated. A cumulative cap of GBP 625\,000 per organ
 isation across all UK Global Screen Fund strands over any three-year perio
 d also applies.\n\nOrganisation: British Film Institute (UK Global Screen 
 Fund\, backed by DCMS)\nLocation: United Kingdom (applications from the UK
 -based lead development studio)\nAward: Non-recoupable grant towards inter
 national marketing and release activity\; the award range is not published
  on the fund page. A cap of GBP 625\,000 applies across all UKGSF strands 
 per organisation over any three-year period. No application fee.\nDuration
 : Single release-activity award\; apply no later than eight weeks before t
 he funded activity begins.\n\nMore: https://www.bfi.org.uk/get-funding-sup
 port/funding-support-international-activity/uk-global-screen-fund/uk-globa
 l-screen-fund-ukgsf-international-distribution-video-game-release-funding?
 utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.bfi.org.uk/get-funding-support/funding-support-internationa
 l-activity/uk-global-screen-fund/uk-global-screen-fund-ukgsf-international
