UID:bfi-national-lottery-creative-challenge-fund-round-2-2026@artificialnou
 veau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260921
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260922
SUMMARY:Deadline: BFI National Lottery Creative Challenge Fund (Round Two)
DESCRIPTION:The Creative Challenge Fund does not fund films directly. It fu
 nds the organisations that run project-development programmes for UK creat
 ives working on narrative\, documentary or animation features\, or on narr
 ative immersive media projects. The BFI's stated aim is to decentralise de
 velopment away from a small number of London-centric gatekeepers and build
  a wider\, more resilient ecosystem of talent-development providers across
  the UK\, with a recently added emphasis on independent producers. ELIGIBI
 LITY: only legally constituted UK-based organisations may apply. Individua
 l filmmakers seeking development money should look to the BFI Filmmaking F
 und's Development strand instead. TIMING: Round One closed in March 2026 a
 nd has made its first awards. Round Two closes Monday 21 September 2026\, 
 with funded programme activity required to begin between 1 January and 30 
 June 2027. NOTE: award amounts are not published on the fund page. Success
 ful applicants must prominently credit BFI National Lottery support.\n\nOr
 ganisation: British Film Institute (BFI National Lottery)\nLocation: Unite
 d Kingdom (UK-based organisations running development programmes for UK cr
 eatives)\nAward: Award amounts are not published on the fund page. No appl
 ication fee.\nDuration: Funded programme activity must start between 1 Jan
 uary and 30 June 2027 and\, in most cases\, be delivered within 12 months 
 unless the applicant is running multiple editions.\n\nMore: https://www.bf
 i.org.uk/get-funding-support/create-films-tv-or-new-formats-storytelling/b
 fi-national-lottery-creative-challenge-fund?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.bfi.org.uk/get-funding-support/create-films-tv-or-new-forma
 ts-storytelling/bfi-national-lottery-creative-challenge-fund?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United Kingdom (UK-based organisations running development program
 mes for UK creatives)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:lse-digipulse-research-officer-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260722
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260723
SUMMARY:Deadline: LSE Research Officer: DigiPulse\, Digital Futures for Chi
 ldren Centre
DESCRIPTION:DigiPulse is a three-year longitudinal\, international research
  project in LSE's Digital Futures for Children centre investigating the re
 al-time relationships between children's smartphone use and their wellbein
 g\, with data collected in the UK\, Brazil and Kenya. The project combines
  passive smartphone tracking\, Ecological Momentary Assessment (EMA) and l
 ongitudinal surveys with around 750 children and young people aged 10-17. 
 THE ROLE: the Research Officer plays a central part in project management\
 , development\, data collection and analysis\, with particular responsibil
 ity for developing and refining EMA instruments\, contributing to the rese
 arch literature and hypotheses\, supporting participatory and consultative
  work with children\, and conducting statistical analysis and producing fi
 ndings\, working closely with partners in the UK\, Brazil and Kenya. REQUI
 REMENTS: a completed PhD in a relevant discipline (e.g. media and communic
 ations\, psychology\, psychiatry\, sociology\, education\, or computationa
 l/data social science)\; experience developing surveys or questionnaire in
 struments\; experience designing or conducting longitudinal research studi
 es\; and experience with EMA\, experience-sampling or other intensive long
 itudinal data collection methods. APPLY via jobs.lse.ac.uk\; questions to 
 k.g.ringmar-sylwander@lse.ac.uk. Closing date 22 July 2026 (23:59 UK time)
 \; late applications are not accepted.\n\nOrganisation: London School of E
 conomics and Political Science (LSE)\, Department of Media and Communicati
 ons\nLocation: London\, UK (hybrid working)\nAward: GBP 43\,277 to 51\,714
  per year inclusive of London allowance\, with potential to progress to GB
 P 55\,497. Full-time (1.0 FTE)\, funded until December 2028. Benefits: occ
 upational pension scheme\, generous annual leave\, hybrid working\, traini
 ng and development. No application fee.\nDuration: Full-time fixed-term po
 st\, funded until December 2028\n\nMore: https://jobs.lse.ac.uk/Vacancies/
 W/2504/0/471333/15539/research-officer-digipulse-digital-futures-for-child
 ren-centre/Referral?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
URL:https://jobs.lse.ac.uk/Vacancies/W/2504/0/471333/15539/research-officer
 -digipulse-digital-futures-for-children-centre/Referral?utm_source=artific
 ialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:London\, UK (hybrid working)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:corridor-daisy-chain-commission-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260803
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260804
SUMMARY:Deadline: Corridor: DAISY CHAIN Artist Commission (Adur\, West Suss
 ex)
DESCRIPTION:Corridor seeks a socially-engaged artist based in the South Eas
 t of England working with moving image / lens-based media for DAISY CHAIN\
 , marking the 60th anniversary of Vera Chytilova's experimental film Daisi
 es (1966). The commissioned artist will work with a group of LGBTQIA+ youn
 g people aged 15-26 in Adur (West Sussex) to co-create new artworks: a 2-3
  minute moving image work and a series of 2D collage or mixed media artwor
 ks for public exhibition and screenings. DAISY CHAIN commissions six new a
 rtist moving image works overall (three England-based artists working with
  older women\, young women and LGBTQIA+ youth\; three artists in Czechia)\
 , developed in partnership with the National Film Museum in Prague (NaFilM
 ) and Brighton-based videoclub\, with results toured across England and Cz
 echia in 2027. EXPECTATIONS: devise about eight hands-on workshops incorpo
 rating film\, collage and mixed media (participants won't necessarily have
  an arts background)\; participate in 4-6 online peer sessions on collabor
 ative practice led by artist Annis Joslin\; complete exhibition-ready artw
 orks on time and to budget\; maintain a transparent dialogue on authorship
  with participants. Artists must have a participatory practice and experie
 nce of working creatively with young people. Note: to create a safe space\
 , workshops will not be publicly labelled as LGBTQIA+. FEE: GBP 4\,200 inc
 l. VAT plus travel and a materials budget. TIMELINE: shortlist notified 7 
 August\, online interviews 12 August 2026\; launch event in Adur/Worthing 
 March 2027. DEADLINE: 10am\, 3 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Corridor Proj
 ects\nLocation: Adur and Worthing\, West Sussex\, UK. Open to a socially-e
 ngaged artist based in the South East of England working with moving image
  / lens-based media.\nAward: GBP 4\,200 artist fee (inclusive of VAT) paid
  in instalments\, plus travel\, and an additional budget for materials for
  creative production\, workshops and exhibition outputs (e.g. print). No a
 pplication fee.\nDuration: September 2026 to July 2027: workshops Septembe
 r-January\, post-production to February 2027\, UK and Czech tour March-Jul
 y 2027\n\nMore: https://www.corridorprojects.org.uk/daisy-chain-commission
 ?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.corridorprojects.org.uk/daisy-chain-commission?utm_source=a
 rtificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Adur and Worthing\, West Sussex\, UK. Open to a socially-engaged a
 rtist based in the South East of England working with moving image / lens-
 based media.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:modern-art-oxford-micro-commissions-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260726
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260727
SUMMARY:Deadline: Modern Art Oxford: Collaborative Micro-commissions Open C
 all 2026
DESCRIPTION:Modern Art Oxford marks its 60th anniversary with an open call 
 for three collaborative micro-commissions responding to the question: how 
 can collective practice/s help us to embrace uncertainty and complexity? C
 ollectives\, duos\, partnerships and collaborative groups based across the
  South East of England are invited to propose new small-scale experimental
  works for a group exhibition in the Ground Floor Gallery\, running alongs
 ide a major solo exhibition by Mike Nelson\, who is also on the selection 
 panel. Proposals may take the form of multidisciplinary research\, site-re
 sponsive work\, grassroots organising\, performance\, visual art\, sound\,
  poetry or other creative practices\; ideas should respond to the theme of
  collective practice and uncertainty\, explore collaborative approaches\, 
 experiment across disciplines\, be achievable within the budget and timeli
 ne\, and be original to this open call (building on existing research is f
 ine). WHO: groups of two or more people\, including established artist col
 lectives\, newly formed collaborations\, interdisciplinary partnerships\, 
 informal or community-led groups\, and family collaborations\, based in th
 e Arts Council England South East area (Oxfordshire\, Berkshire\, Buckingh
 amshire\, Hampshire and Isle of Wight\, Surrey\, Kent\, East Sussex\, West
  Sussex). SUPPORT: each of the three selected collectives receives a GBP 1
 \,000 artist fee\, up to GBP 500 production budget\, curatorial mentorship
 \, four months of exhibition display\, installation photography\, promotio
 n\, technical and production support\, and transport support within the So
 uth East. TIMELINE: online briefing and Q&A 15 June 2026 (email creativele
 arning@modernartoxford.org.uk for the link)\; selection confirmed 14 Augus
 t 2026\; production August to November 2026\; preview party 4 December 202
 6\; exhibition 5 December 2026 to April 2027. Apply via Google Forms\; an 
 information pack PDF and FAQ are on the call page. DEADLINE: Sunday 26 Jul
 y 2026\, 23:59.\n\nOrganisation: Modern Art Oxford\nLocation: Oxford\, UK.
  Open to collectives\, duos\, partnerships and collaborative groups based 
 in the Arts Council England South East area (Oxfordshire\, Berkshire\, Buc
 kinghamshire\, Hampshire and Isle of Wight\, Surrey\, Kent\, East Sussex\,
  West Sussex).\nAward: GBP 1\,000 artist fee per selected collective\, plu
 s up to GBP 500 production budget\, curatorial mentorship from the Modern 
 Art Oxford team\, four months of public exhibition display\, professional 
 installation photography\, promotion\, technical and production support\, 
 artwork transport support within the South East\, peer networking\, and in
 clusion in a public preview event. No application fee.\nDuration: Producti
 on August to November 2026\; install 23 November to 4 December 2026\; exhi
 bition 5 December 2026 to April 2027\n\nMore: https://modernartoxford.org.
 uk/blog/open-call-2026?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=re
 ferral
URL:https://modernartoxford.org.uk/blog/open-call-2026?utm_source=artificia
 lnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Oxford\, UK. Open to collectives\, duos\, partnerships and collabo
 rative groups based in the Arts Council England South East area (Oxfordshi
 re\, Berkshire\, Buckinghamshire\, Hampshire and Isle of Wight\, Surrey\, 
 Kent\, East Sussex\, West Sussex).
END:VEVENT
