UID:govai-uk-winter-fellowship-2027-research-track@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260712
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260713
SUMMARY:Deadline: GovAI UK Winter Fellowship 2027 - Research Track
DESCRIPTION:GovAI's UK Winter Fellowship (Research Track) is a three-month 
 in-person fellowship in London for researchers and policy professionals se
 eking to enter or advance careers in AI governance and policy. Fellows con
 duct independent research on a topic of their choice\, paired with a GovAI
  supervisor from the team or network\; the first two weeks are spent explo
 ring the AI governance landscape before a research proposal is finalised. 
 Research outputs may include a report\, white paper\, journal article\, op
 -ed\, or blog post targeted at an audience relevant to AI governance. Alon
 gside the project\, fellows attend expert Q&As\, weekly seminars\, skills 
 workshops\, work-in-progress meetings\, and social events\, and are encour
 aged to discuss follow-on career opportunities with GovAI's team and netwo
 rk. GovAI alumni have gone on to roles in US\, UK\, and EU government\; le
 ading AI companies (Anthropic\, DeepMind\, OpenAI)\; top think tanks (CSET
 \, RAND)\; and leading universities (Oxford\, Cambridge). AMOUNT: £12\,00
 0 salary for three months\, plus travel support to London and weekday lunc
 h. Visa sponsorship for a 3-month temporary work visa is available\; succe
 ssful visa applicants must remain in their country of application while th
 e visa is processed. ELIGIBILITY: open to a wide range of backgrounds (gov
 ernment\, academia\, industry\, civil society)\; no strict degree requirem
 ents\; relevant areas include public policy\, political science\, computer
  science\, economics\, biosecurity\, cybersecurity\, China studies\, and r
 isk management. Senior candidates who need accommodations should email fel
 lowships@governance.ai with subject line 'senior candidate winter fellowsh
 ip 2027' and a CV. SELECTION CRITERIA: quality and clarity of written work
 \, relevant expertise\, judgement in prioritising research directions\, an
 d team fit (intellectual honesty\, openness to feedback\, comfort with unc
 ertainty). APPLICATION PROCESS: (1) written application and automated abst
 ract reasoning assessment\; (2) paid remote work test (August 2026)\; (3) 
 remote interview and reference checks (September 2026)\; decisions communi
 cated October 2026. Deadline: 12 July 2026\, 23:59 BST.\n\nOrganisation: C
 entre for the Governance of AI (GovAI)\nLocation: London\, UK\; in-person\
 , full-time.\nAward: £12\,000 salary for the three-month term\, plus trav
 el support to London and weekday lunch provided. Visa sponsorship (3-month
  temporary work visa) available. No application fee.\nDuration: 3 months\,
  18 January to 9 April 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.governance.ai/post/winte
 r-fellowship-2027-research-track?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm
 _medium=referral
URL:https://www.governance.ai/post/winter-fellowship-2027-research-track?ut
 m_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:London\, UK\; in-person\, full-time.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:sound-image-2026-call-for-works-greenwich@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260619
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260620
SUMMARY:Deadline: SOUND/IMAGE 2026: "Artistic Intelligence" - Call for Work
 s
DESCRIPTION:SOUND/IMAGE 2026 is the 11th edition of the University of Green
 wich festival exploring sound and image practice\, running 5-8 November 20
 26 in London. This year's theme is "Artistic Intelligence": a critical ref
 lection on creative choice\, agency\, and authenticity in the context of a
 lgorithmic and AI-mediated art making. The festival cites reference points
  from Vera Molnár\, Pauline Oliveros\, John Cage\, Iannis Xenakis\, Ryoji
  Ikeda\, and Refik Anadol. Special consideration is given to students\, ap
 prentices\, and emerging artists\; submissions are welcome from composers\
 , filmmakers\, artists\, performers\, and architects. CATEGORIES ACCEPTED:
  sound and music works\; audiovisual works\; talks\; artist statements\; w
 orkshops and practical demonstrations\; live performances\; installations.
  THEMATIC AREAS: embodied knowledge and lived experience in aesthetic judg
 ement\; creative choice vs chance encounters\; ownership\, authenticity\, 
 and AI co-creation\; human and algorithmic capability\; spatial and immers
 ive audio-visual forms\; interdisciplinary practice (CreaTech)\; practice 
 research. SUBMISSION RULES: works under 15 minutes in duration (installati
 ons exempt from duration limit)\; maximum three submissions per artist acr
 oss all categories\; artists must attend and present in person\; submit se
 parately for each submission via Microsoft CMT. FESTIVAL PASS: all accepte
 d artists must purchase a festival pass at a reduced rate of £25. Notific
 ations before end of July 2026. Deadline: 19 June 2026\, 23:59 UTC+1 (exte
 nded from 12 June). Submit at https://blogs.gre.ac.uk/sound-image/sound-im
 age-2026-call-for-works/.\n\nOrganisation: University of Greenwich\nLocati
 on: University of Greenwich\, London\, UK\; in-person attendance required.
 \nAward: No payment to artists. All accepted artists must purchase a festi
 val pass at a reduced rate of £25 (covers catering and technical support)
 .\nDuration: Festival runs 5-8 November 2026.\n\nMore: https://blogs.gre.a
 c.uk/sound-image/sound-image-2026-call-for-works/?utm_source=artificialnou
 veaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://blogs.gre.ac.uk/sound-image/sound-image-2026-call-for-works/?ut
 m_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:University of Greenwich\, London\, UK\; in-person attendance requi
 red.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:freelands-learning-through-making-fund-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T074454Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260911
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260912
SUMMARY:Deadline: Freelands Foundation: Learning Through Making Fund
DESCRIPTION:The Learning Through Making fund supports UK-based visual art o
 rganisations to bring opportunities for making and material exploration in
 to their art education work. Freelands Foundation is looking for explorato
 ry projects that embrace openness\, collaboration\, and iteration -- enabl
 ing organisations to work with materials in an expansive way\, unpicking p
 reconceptions about making and material literacy without predefined outcom
 es. ELIGIBLE ACTIVITIES: providing materials\, transport\, or access to ex
 pertise and facilities\; action-research trials such as a new series of wo
 rkshops or events developing material literacy\; adding a making-focused e
 lement to existing activity. Projects may range from a few days to several
  months\, but must take place between 1 January and 31 December 2027. AMOU
 NT: up to £25\,000\; funding provided no earlier than December 2026. ELIG
 IBILITY: UK-based visual art organisations run with a charitable purpose a
 nd for public benefit\; eligible types include charities registered in Eng
 land and Wales\, Scotland\, or Northern Ireland\; exempt charities\; galle
 ries\, museums\, or organisations within a Local Authority or larger chari
 table body (e.g. universities)\; and Community Interest Companies or Commu
 nity Benefit Societies meeting specific criteria (charitable purposes\, as
 set lock\, no dividend distribution\, ability to segregate restricted fund
 s). Organisations with a prior Freelands Foundation grant relationship are
  eligible\; you may not apply for activity already funded by Freelands Fou
 ndation. Individuals are not eligible. HOW TO APPLY: download the Applicat
 ion Form\, Application Guidance\, and optional Access Form from freelandsf
 oundation.co.uk\; email completed form to grants@freelandsfoundation.co.uk
  with subject line 'LTM Fund - Application'\; one additional page of image
 s or diagrams may be included. APPLICATION SUPPORT SESSIONS (online): 9 Ju
 ly 2026\, 10:30am-12pm\; 12 August 2026\, 10:30am-12pm. KEY DATES: applica
 tions open 17 June 2026\; close 11 September 2026 at 12pm\; outcomes share
 d 23 November 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Freelands Foundation\nLocation: UK (E
 ngland\, Northern Ireland\, Scotland\, Wales)\; activity must occur within
  the United Kingdom.\nAward: Up to £25\,000. No application fee.\nDuratio
 n: Projects of any length\, taking place between 1 January and 31 December
  2027. Funding provided no earlier than December 2026.\n\nMore: https://fr
 eelandsfoundation.co.uk/engage/apply/grants/learning-through-making-fund?u
 tm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://freelandsfoundation.co.uk/engage/apply/grants/learning-through-
 making-fund?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:UK (England\, Northern Ireland\, Scotland\, Wales)\; activity must
  occur within the United Kingdom.
END:VEVENT
